comp-kvvax2yw1.html: We are a wholistic, person-centered psychology practice based in Chicago and its suburbs. We are a diverse, collaborative, community-oriented organization that provides telehealth and in-person psychological services.

comp-kvvax31z.html: Whether you're interested in scheduling an appointment for therapy or assessment, or you're not sure where to begin, our intake coordinator will get you scheduled to meet with one of our clinicians.

comp-kvvbogat.html: Our approach is based on the theory of psychotherapy founded by Carl R. Rogers, which believes that all individuals have the natural capacity for change and growth. We believe that this growth can be nurtured in non-judgmental relationships that are genuine, empathic, and prizing of our unique experiences. Our staff seeks to embody these relational attitudes with all of our clients.

comp-kvvbogbb1.html: We specialize in the evaluation and diagnosis of attention, memory, relational, and emotional difficulties, as well as neurodevelopment and neurodegenerative disorders. Our assessments focus on answering your questions about your difficulties and ways to improve your life. Tell us your goal for assessment and we will help you meet those needs.

comp-kvvbogbn.html: We offer advanced training in classical, nondirective, client-centered psychotherapy and the person-centered approach in the tradition of Carl R. Rogers. We offer training opportunities to graduate students seeking diagnostic, intervention, and advanced psychology practicum externships. We also offer postdoctoral fellowships training opportunities in addition to continuing education and group consultation for practicing clinicians. Our supervisor-consultants are dedicated to training future clinicians in the person-centered approach, and we welcome all trainees and clinicians to contact us for more information about opportunities to advance their careers.

comp-kvvax2z4.html: We believe that all humans have potential for growth

comp-kvvax3122.html:
Margaret S. Warner, Ph.D. (she/her) is a Distinguished Professor at the Illinois School of Professional Psychology at National Louis University in Chicago. Dr. Warner has published widely and has offered many presentations to international groups on “difficult process”, diversity, and the person-centered theory of meaning. She is currently working on a book to be published by PCCS BOOKS called A Very Human Process. Dr. Warner is the 2022 recipient of the Eleanor Criswell Hanna Award, Celebrating Women in Humanistic Psychology for recognition of professional accomplishments that celebrate the achievements and contributions of women in humanistic psychology.

 

Dr. Warner received a doctorate in Behavioral Sciences from the Committee on Human Development of the University of Chicago in 1979. Her clinical training was undertaken at the Chicago Counseling and Psychotherapy Center, an offshoot of the original Counseling Center founded by Carl Rogers at the University of Chicago.

​

She is a non-directive client-centered therapist who has practiced for over 35 years, with a particular emphasis on working with clients experiencing “difficult process." Dr. Warner also has a particular interest in a person-centered approach to diversity issues. She co- founded a group called “Face to Face with Diversity” that conducted a day-long person -centered diversity group at the Chicago 2000 conference and afterward ran diversity groups and classes and conducted diversity-oriented person-centered training for clinical psychology students.

 

Dr. Warner was a co-founder of the Minor in Client-Centered and Experiential Psychology at the Illinois School of Professional Psychology. With a group of volunteers, Dr. Warner convened Chicago 2000: The Fifth International Conference in Client-Centered and Experiential Psychotherapies, the first time that this conference had been held in the United States. She was a founding member of the World Association for Person-Centered and Experiential Psychotherapy and Counseling.

comp-kvvax3122__item-kvuv6sme.html: Dr. Olivia Beers, PsyD (she/her) earned her Doctorate in Clinical Psychology from the Illinois School of Professional Psychology with a concentration in Neuropsychology. She completed an APA-accredited internship at the Nebraska-Western Iowa Veteran Affairs Hospital. She is currently pursuing her prescriptive privileges for clinical psychologists in the APA accredited psychopharmacology program at the Chicago School of Professional Psychology. Dr. Beers has experience in conducting assessments for pre-surgical candidates, movement disorders, dementia, psychiatric comorbidities, and traumatic brain injuries. Her clinical interests are in neurodegenerative diseases and movement disorders within the adult population.

comp-kvvax3122__item-ld08edq7.html:
Travis Musich, MA (he/him) is a nondirective, client-centered therapist with over 15+ years of experience working in the mental health field. Travis is a strong advocate and member of the LGBT+ community. To this end, his therapeutic approach is sensitive and responsive to his clients’ diverse backgrounds as they shape an individual’s life experiences. In addition to working with anxiety, depression, grief, and trauma, Travis' clinical training has focused on client-centered therapy and working with individuals struggling with early childhood trauma, dissociation, psychosis, and other of difficult experiences. In therapy, Travis' approach is nondirective, genuine, warm, and empathic.

 

He is a clinical psychology doctoral student at the Illinois School of Professional Psychology at National Louis University where he also received his M.A. in clinical psychology. Travis received his B.S. in psychology from Loyola University Chicago. Travis completed his pre-doctoral psychology internship with University Health & Counseling Services at University of Wisconsin-Whitewater. Travis received classical training in the person-centered approach at Chicago Counseling Associates under the supervision and mentorship of Marjorie Witty and Carolynn Schneider. As a graduate teaching assistant, Travis trained closely under Margaret S. Warner, Ph.D. while co-teaching courses on person-centered psychotherapy, health and human dysfunction, and encounter groups at the Illinois School of Professional Psychology. Prior to his graduate training, Travis worked with adults and adolescents on inpatient behavioral health services at Northwestern Medicine and NorthShore University health systems.
